<paragraph blockId="27.[812,1421,832,1163]" pageId="27" pageNumber="678">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,974,832,856]" pageId="27" pageNumber="678">Identification.</emphasis>
This species is characterized by having terrestrial habit, short internodes, fibrous persistent cataphylls, D-shaped petioles in cross section, broadly ovate blades, cordate at base, and inflorescences with green spathes. On Cerro Pirre, 
<taxonomicName box="[1156,1421,969,993]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Philodendron" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="27" pageNumber="678" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="grandipes">
<emphasis box="[1156,1421,969,993]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="678">Philodendron grandipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only species of the genus that consistently have terrestrial habit. Due to the terrestrial habit and the ovate blades, it can be confused with individuals of the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[814,934,1105,1129]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Adelonema" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="27" pageNumber="678" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[814,934,1105,1129]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="678">Adelonema</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which differs substantially in having armed petioles and diminutive puberulent blades.
</paragraph>
